<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,774,1021]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
For a long time “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1813" box="[392,701,774,800]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="commersoni">
<emphasis box="[392,701,774,800]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Hipposideros commersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” was considered to occur across the African continent, but 
<bibRefCitation author="McWilliam" box="[189,438,811,837]" firstAuthor="McWilliam" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" refId="ref269791" refString="McWilliam A. N. 1982. Adaptive Responses to Seasonality in Four Species of Microchiroptera in Coastal Kenya. PhD thesis, University of Aberdeen, UK. Available from http: // aulib. abdn. ac. uk / F /? func = findb &amp; find _ code = SYS &amp; request = 001620585 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="url" year="1982">McWilliam (1982: 9)</bibRefCitation>
found 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1845" box="[521,585,812,837]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[521,585,812,837]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be specifically different from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1813" box="[970,1113,812,837]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="commersoni">
<emphasis box="[970,1113,812,837]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">commersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which ultimately led to the restriction of the usage of the name “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1813" box="[674,982,847,873]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="commersoni">
<emphasis box="[674,982,847,873]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Hipposideros commersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” for populations from 
<collectingCountry box="[1257,1399,847,873]" name="Madagascar" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
only. 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[256,519,884,911]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="385 - 387" refId="ref263209" refString="Happold M. 2013 k. Hipposideros gigas Giant Leaf-nosed Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 385 - 387. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="k">Happold (2013k: 385)</bibRefCitation>
indicates that both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1845" box="[756,820,885,910]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[756,820,885,910]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[881,967,885,910]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vittatus">
<emphasis box="[881,967,885,910]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">vittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(or its synonym 
<emphasis box="[1173,1323,885,910]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">marungensis</emphasis>
) were reported to occur sympatrically, which makes them separate species as well (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="312 - 567" refId="ref273235" refString="Simmons N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. In: Wilson D. E. &amp; Reeder D. M. (eds) Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference: 312 - 567. The John Hopkins University Press, Baltimore." type="book chapter" year="2005">Simmons 2005: 372</bibRefCitation>
, 377). Unfortunately, however, as mentioned by these two authors, this split probably makes it necessary to re-examine all material collected prior to 2005 to assess their identification.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,1061,1307]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[314,639,1061,1087]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[428,494,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 44)
</bibRefCitation>
report the two “subspecies”, they only provided a map for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[189,440,1098,1123]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="commersoni" subSpecies="gigas">
<emphasis box="[189,440,1098,1123]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">H. commersoni gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(map 50), which also contained the data for the other form. The distribution map provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[340,604,1134,1161]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="385 - 387" refId="ref263209" refString="Happold M. 2013 k. Hipposideros gigas Giant Leaf-nosed Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 385 - 387. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="k">Happold (2013k: 386)</bibRefCitation>
indicates that “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1845" box="[791,893,1135,1160]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[791,893,1135,1160]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">H. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” primarily occurs in western Africa to the 
<collectingCountry box="[189,462,1171,1197]" name="Republic of the Congo" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Republic of the Congo</collectingCountry>
, coastal 
<collectingCountry box="[564,650,1171,1197]" name="Angola" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Angola</collectingCountry>
and in the coastal areas around the border between 
<collectingCountry box="[1271,1348,1171,1197]" name="Kenya" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[189,298,1207,1233]" name="Tanzania" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
. Furthermore, she plots a few isolated records in the eastern part of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1147,1211,1207,1233]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">DRC</collectingCountry>
. The SDM map is fairly similar, although we connect the western African populations with those from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1286,1346,1244,1270]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">DRC</collectingCountry>
and believe the eastern African populations represent 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[769,1036,1281,1306]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Macronycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vittatus">
<emphasis box="[769,1036,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Macronycteris vittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1845" box="[1179,1282,1281,1306]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[1179,1282,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">M. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
